If you are struggling to hit that 90° mark during manufacturing, the issue usually boils down to one of three things: Springback (if bending), Thermal Distortion (if welding), or Accumulated Tolerances (if assembling tabs).

Since your CAD model shows a "Tab-and-Slot" design, here is how to troubleshoot and fix the 90-degree error on the shop floor:

1. The "Weld Pull" Problem (Most Common)
If you are welding that blue plate into the slots, the weld bead acts like a cooling rubber band. As the molten metal solidifies, it shrinks and pulls the plate toward the weld.

The Fix: "Preset" the part. If your plate keeps ending up at 88°, tilt it to 92° before welding. The shrinkage will pull it back to 90°.

Tack Sequence: Place a small tack weld on the outside of the 90° corner first, then the inside. This balances the tension.

2. Tab-and-Slot "Slop"
In CAD, a 3 mm tab fits perfectly in a 3 mm slot. In reality, laser or plasma cutters have a "kerf" (the width of the cut).

The Issue: If the slot is 0.2 mm wider than the tab, the plate can lean several degrees in either direction.

The Fix: Use a Squaring Jig or a Magnetic 90° Square during the assembly phase. Do not trust the slots to hold the angle for you; they only locate the part, they don't square it.

3. Press Brake Springback
If the blue plate is being bent from a single sheet of metal:

The Physics: Every material has an elastic limit. When you bend to 90°, it relaxes back.

The Fix: You must Overbend. For standard cold-rolled steel, you typically bend to roughly 91 
∘
  or 92 
∘
  so that it "springs" back to a perfect 90°.

Tooling: Ensure the V-die on the press brake is narrow enough. If the die is too wide, the radius becomes inconsistent, making the angle hard to hit.

4. Internal Fillets / Burrs
Check the corners of your tabs and slots.

The Issue: If the laser cutter leaves a small rounded "fillet" in the corner of the slot, or if there is a burr (dross) on the bottom, the blue plate won't sit flush against the rail. Even a tiny piece of debris will prevent a true 90° sit.

The Fix: "Dogbone" the corners of your slots in CAD (adding tiny circular cutouts at the corners) to ensure the tab can sit perfectly flat without interference.

Summary Table: Troubleshooting the Angle
Symptom	Likely Cause	Solution
Angle < 90° (Closing up)	Weld shrinkage or under-bending.	Preset the angle wider or increase press brake depth.
Angle > 90° (Opening up)	Not enough clamping or over-bending.	Use 90° corner clamps during tacking.
Angle is inconsistent	Burrs in slots or uneven table.	Grind tabs clean; use a precision granite or steel flat-top table.
